# Cloudflare Pages / Netlify static-headers convention (ignored by other
# hosts — notably GitHub Pages, which serves no custom headers at all; see
# docs/config.md "SVG asset trust model" for what that means for that
# deployment target). Hashed build output is immutable; the WASM is
# version-pinned but served under a stable filename, so it gets a day of
# browser cache (the app's own versioned Cache Storage makes browser-cache
# lifetime mostly moot anyway).
/assets/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
/wasm/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400

# M13 — design/config sources (including the SVGs mounted under /scad/: use/
# include assets consumed by OpenSCAD's import()/surface(), plus the copied
# logo/design-icon files) and the generated /icon.svg are trusted OPERATOR
# input, not sandboxed third-party content — see docs/config.md "SVG asset
# trust model". They're safe wherever they're actually used (<img>, <use>,
# CSS, OpenSCAD's WASM FS), but an SVG can carry <script>, and a browser that
# is navigated to one *directly* would otherwise execute it in this app's
# origin. These headers are cheap defense-in-depth against exactly that direct
# -navigation case; they don't restrict — and can't break — the app's own
# <img>/<use>/CSS/import() consumption of the same files, since a CSP header
# only governs the fetched resource when *it* is the top-level document (or an
# embedded document, e.g. an iframe), not when it's decoded as an image or
# mounted into the WASM filesystem.
/scad/*
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'none'; sandbox
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
/icon.svg
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'none'; sandbox
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
/*.svg
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'none'; sandbox
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
